    "question": "How does MCP (Model Context Protocol) work and who uses it?",
    "answer": "The Model Context Protocol (MCP) is an open-source standard for connecting artificial intelligence (AI) applications to external tools, systems, and data sources [1, 2]. Introduced by Anthropic in November 2024, it works by providing a universal, standardized interface that allows AI models to perform tasks like reading files and executing functions without needing custom-built connectors for each tool [2].\n\n### How it Works\nMCP aims to reduce development time and complexity by creating a common framework for AI integration [1]. Before MCP, developers often had to create unique connectors for each data source or tool an AI needed to access [2]. MCP solves this by establishing a standard protocol that re-uses concepts from the Language Server Protocol (LSP) and is transported over JSON-RPC 2.0 [2]. This allows developers to build a connection once and have it be usable across any AI application that supports the protocol, enabling more capable AI agents that can access data and take actions on a user's behalf [1].\n\n### Who Uses It\nMCP was developed by Anthropic but is an open protocol with broad ecosystem support [1, 2].\n*   **AI Providers**: Following its announcement, major AI providers including OpenAI and Google DeepMind adopted the protocol [2].\n*   **AI Applications**: AI assistants like Claude and ChatGPT support MCP [1].\n*   **Development Tools**: Coding platforms and Integrated Development Environments (IDEs) such as Visual Studio Code, Cursor, and Sourcegraph have adopted MCP to provide AI coding assistants with real-time access to project context [1, 2].\n\nThe protocol was released with software development kits (SDKs) in languages like Python, TypeScript, C#, and Java to facilitate adoption [2].",
